import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from scipy.stats import norm

# List of variables
variables_of_interest = ["sbp", "tobacco", "ldl", "adiposity", "typea", "obesity", "alcohol", "age"]

try:
    # Read the dataset from the CSV file
    df = pd.read_csv('HeartDisease.csv')
    
    # Set up subplots for each histogram
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=4, figsize=(18, 8))
    fig.suptitle("Histograms with Normal Curves", fontsize=16)
    
    for i, var in enumerate(variables_of_interest):
        row, col = i // 4, i % 4  # Calculate the subplot position
        ax = axes[row, col]

        # Create a histogram
        sns.histplot(df[var], kde=True, ax=ax, color='blue', bins=20, label=f'{var} Histogram')
        
        # Overlay a normal distribution curve
        mean, std = df[var].mean(), df[var].std()
        x = np.linspace(df[var].min(), df[var].max(), 1000)
        y = norm.pdf(x, mean, std)
        ax.plot(x, y, color='red', label=f'Normal Curve')
        
        ax.set_title(var)
        ax.legend()
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)
    plt.show()

except FileNotFoundError:
    print("File not found. Please check the file path and make sure the file exists.")
except Exception as e:
    print("An error occurred:", e)

import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# List of variables
variables_of_interest = ["sbp", "tobacco", "ldl", "adiposity", "typea", "obesity", "alcohol", "age"]

try:
    # Read the dataset from the CSV file
    df = pd.read_csv('HeartDisease.csv')
    
    # Set up subplots for Q-Q plots
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=4, figsize=(18, 8))
    fig.suptitle("Quantile-Quantile (Q-Q) Plots", fontsize=16)
    
    for i, var in enumerate(variables_of_interest):
        row, col = i // 4, i % 4  # Calculate the subplot position
        ax = axes[row, col]

        # Create the Q-Q plot
        sm.qqplot(df[var], line='45', ax=ax)
        
        ax.set_title(var)
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)
    plt.show()

except FileNotFoundError:
    print("File not found. Please check the file path and make sure the file exists.")
except Exception as e:
    print("An error occurred:", e)

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from scipy import stats

# Part 4
# Declare predictors
X = df[['sbp', 'tobacco', 'ldl', 'adiposity', 'typea', 'obesity', 'alcohol', 'age']]
y = df[['chd']]

# Convert categorical data to numerical
cat_pred = df[['famhist']]
dummies = pd.get_dummies(cat_pred, drop_first = True)
X = pd.concat([X, dummies], axis = 1)

# Split data into training(80%) and testing(20%)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test= train_test_split(X, y, test_size= 0.2, random_state= 16)

# Instantiate the model
logreg = LogisticRegression(solver='lbfgs', max_iter=1000, random_state = 16)

# Fit the model with data
logreg.fit(X_train, y_train.values.ravel())
y_pred = logreg.predict(X_test)

#part 7

variables = ['sbp_lbmd', 'tobacco_lbmd', 'ldl_lbmd', 'obesity_lbmd', 'alcohol_lbmd']

for variable in variables:
    plt.figure()
    plt.hist(df[variable], bins=20, density=True, alpha=0.6, color='blue', label=f'{variable} Histogram')
    mu, std = df[variable].mean(), df[variable].std()
    xmin, xmax = df[variable].min(), df[variable].max()
    x = np.linspace(xmin, xmax, 100)
    p = stats.norm.pdf(x, mu, std)
    plt.plot(x, p, 'red', linewidth=2, label='Normal Curve')
    plt.title(f'Histogram with Normal Curve: {variable}')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
